"     Patient information: Meckel&rsquo;s diverticulum (The Basics)",
"    </div>",
"    <span class=\"view\">",
"     View in",
"     <a class=\"lang\" href=\"./es-419/meckels-diverticulum-the-basics?source=topic_page\">",
"      Spanish",
"     </a>",
"    </span>",
"    <a class=\"contributor contributor_credentials\" href=\"./authors-and-editors/patient-information\">",
"     Written by the doctors and editors at UpToDate",
"    </a>",
"    <div id=\"topicText\">",
"     <p class=\"headingAnchor\" id=\"H29115316\">",
"      <span class=\"h1\">",
"       What is Meckel&rsquo;s diverticulum?",
"      </span>",
"      &nbsp;&mdash;&nbsp;Meckel&rsquo;s diverticulum is a small pouch that sticks out from the wall of the small intestine (",
"      <a class=\"graphic graphic_figure graphicRef66110 \" href=\"mobipreview.htm?28/27/29107\">",
"       figure 1",
"      </a>",
"      ). People who have this condition were born with it. The pouch is made of tissue that was part of their digestive system when they were still in their mother&rsquo;s womb. This tissue goes away before birth in most people, but a few people still have it.",
"     </p>",
"     <p class=\"headingAnchor\" id=\"H29115331\">",
"      <span class=\"h1\">",
"       What are the symptoms of Meckel&rsquo;s diverticulum?",
"      </span>",
"      &nbsp;&mdash;&nbsp;Many people have a Meckel&rsquo;s diverticulum and never have symptoms. About half the people who do have symptoms are children younger than 10 years old. &nbsp;",
"     </p>",
"     <p>",
"      Symptoms can include:",
"     </p>",
"     <p>",
"      <ul class=\"bullet-block\">",
"       <li>",
"        Blood in bowel movements &ndash; They might look red, or black and sticky.",
"       </li>",
"       <li>",
"        Belly pain",
"       </li>",
"       <li>",
"        Not passing gas or having bowel movements &ndash; This can mean something is blocking the intestine.",
"       </li>",
"      </ul>",
"     </p>",
"     <p class=\"headingAnchor\" id=\"H29115346\">",
"      <span class=\"h1\">",
"       Is there a test for Meckel&rsquo;s diverticulum?",
"      </span>",
"      &nbsp;&mdash;&nbsp;Yes. The doctor or nurse will do an exam and learn about the symptoms. He or she can also order tests. These can include:",
"     </p>",
"     <p>",
"      <ul class=\"bullet-block\">",
"       <li>",
"        A special imaging test called a &ldquo;Meckel scan&rdquo; - In this test, you get a small amount of radioactive material through a thin tube called an &ldquo;IV.&rdquo; The tube goes into a vein. The radioactive material helps doctors see certain types of tissue on imaging tests. It can show abnormal tissue that is often in a Meckel&rsquo;s diverticulum. A day or 2 before a Meckel scan, the doctor might give you medicine to take by mouth. This medicine can help the Meckel scan work better. &nbsp;",
"       </li>",
"       <li>",
"        Other tests to look at the intestines &ndash; These can include an &ldquo;ultrasound&rdquo; or &ldquo;CT scan.&rdquo; These are imaging tests that create pictures of the inside of the body. If you have symptoms of a Meckel&rsquo;s diverticulum, but the Meckel scan does not show abnormal tissue, you might have these other tests.",
"       </li>",
"      </ul>",
"     </p>",
"     <p class=\"headingAnchor\" id=\"H29115363\">",
"      <span class=\"h1\">",
"       How is Meckel&rsquo;s diverticulum treated?",
"      </span>",
"      &nbsp;&mdash;&nbsp;If it causes symptoms, doctors take it out with surgery.",
"     </p>",
"     <p>",
"      Doctors sometimes find a Meckel&rsquo;s diverticulum by accident. This can happen if someone has surgery in the belly for another condition. If they find it in a child, they usually take it out. This can keep it from causing symptoms in the future. If doctors find a Meckel&rsquo;s diverticulum in an adult, they sometimes leave it if it is not causing symptoms.",
"     </p>",
